Analysis of Target Structure  
•  Total Count and Layers  
  – The model uses 8 total blocks arranged in essentially two “layers.”  
    1)  On the ground: two red arches at the front, two green rectangular blocks behind them, and two tall yellow blocks behind the green ones (all on the floor).  
    2)  On top: two yellow half‐cylinders placed atop the red arches.  

•  Spatial Relationships  
  – Front row: Two red arch blocks side‐by‐side.  
  – Directly behind each red arch (on the same floor level): one green upright block.  
  – Behind each green upright block (still on the floor): one tall yellow rectangular block.  
  – Second layer: One yellow half‐cylinder perched on each of the two red arches.  

Selection of Dictionary Blocks  
1) Red Arches (2 needed)  
   – Use the shape labeled “2” in the dictionary, because its arch “faces” front‐to‐back as in the target.  
2) Green Uprights (2 needed)  
   – Use the shape labeled “9,” a green rectangular prism standing upright.  
3) Tall Yellow Blocks (2 needed)  
   – Use “16,” the tall yellow piece that is oriented narrow‐side‐front in the dictionary (matching the target’s narrow front face).  
4) Yellow Half‐Cylinders (2 needed)  
   – Use “14,” the yellow half‐cylinder lying horizontally (flat side down, curved side up).  

Assembly Order  
{  
  Step1: Move block with index 2 (first red arch)  
  Step2: Move block with index 2 (second red arch)  
  Step3: Move block with index 9 (first green upright)  
  Step4: Move block with index 9 (second green upright)  
  Step5: Move block with index 16 (first tall yellow block)  
  Step6: Move block with index 16 (second tall yellow block)  
  Step7: Move block with index 14 (left yellow half‐cylinder)  
  Step8: Move block with index 14 (right yellow half‐cylinder)  
}
